Here's a complete example. I'll walk through the three pieces:

---

### 1. `Tools/ApiTools.cs` — Tool class wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user profile by ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List all posts for a given user.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUserPosts(
        [Description("The numeric user ID whose posts to retrieve")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/users/{userId}/posts", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = false, Destructive = false),
     Description("Create a new post for a user.")]
    public async Task<string> CreatePost(
        [Description("The user ID authoring the post")] int userId,
        [Description("Title of the new post")] string title,
        [Description("Body content of the post")] string body,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = new { userId, title, body };
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsJsonAsync(
            "/posts", payload, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

**Key conventions:**
- `[McpServerToolType]` on the class, `[McpServerTool]` + `[Description]` on every method
- `[Description]` on every parameter — LLMs use these to understand what to pass
- `ReadOnly = false` / `Destructive = false` on the write tool to hint at side effects
- `HttpClient` and `ILogger<T>` come from **constructor injection** (see DI below)

---

### 2. `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: route all logging to stderr so stdout stays clean for JSON-RPC
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Configure the HttpClient that gets injected into ApiTools
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();   // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### 3. How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|---|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the constructor — shared across all tool methods in that class |
| **Method injection** | Static class | Services as extra method parameters — resolved per call |

**What the SDK auto-injects (never appears in the tool schema):**

- Any service registered in DI (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, your own services)
- `CancellationToken`
- `IMcpServer` (for server notifications/logging)
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` (for progress reporting)

The SDK distinguishes user-facing parameters (those with `[Description]`) from injected services by type. Only user-facing parameters appear in the JSON schema sent to LLMs.

In the example above, `AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(...)` registers a **typed `HttpClient`** scoped to `ApiTools`. When a client calls `GetUser`, the SDK instantiates `ApiTools` with the configured `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>`, then invokes the method — all automatically.
